const WSS_APPAREL=`WSS APPAREL REVIEW FRAMEWORK v2.1 — score 6 pillars (Pillar 6 Diversity & Inclusion in Testing is EXCLUDED for now):
PILLAR 1 INCLUSIVE FIT & PROPORTIONAL SIZING: UK 16 must NOT be labelled XL. Size range should span UK 6-24+. Women's proportions, not scaled-down unisex.
PILLAR 2 FUNCTIONAL PERFORMANCE IN USE: Seam placement, waistband stability, torso coverage, chafe after 45+ min. Performance in the intended activity.
PILLAR 3 ADEQUATE SUPPORT STANDARDS: Stated impact level vs experience, cup range A-HH. HARD RULE: a Pillar 3 FAIL caps the OVERALL score at a MAXIMUM of 2 stars.
PILLAR 4 THERMAL REGULATION & MATERIAL PERFORMANCE: Breathability and moisture-wicking claims independently lab-tested under sustained exertion; materials must maintain performance after a minimum 30 wash cycles.
PILLAR 5 GENUINE FEMALE DESIGN: Women-specific cutting, functional pockets, engineering not colour. No "pink it and shrink it".
PILLAR 7 TRANSPARENCY & USER REVIEWS: Published testing data, substantiated claims. HARD RULE: MAXIMUM 3 stars overall without verifiable, published data.
SCORING: 1=Fail 2=Poor 3=Acceptable 4=Very Good 5=Exceptional. Whole numbers per pillar; the Overall may use a half-star.
OVERALL = average of the six pillar scores, then APPLY the hard rules (Pillar 3 fail => max 2.0; no verifiable data => max 3.0).

OUTPUT FORMAT — use these exact H2 headings, in this order. IMPORTANT: do NOT use the word "Pillar" anywhere in the output — use the criterion names only:
## Overview
[Open in the first person with personal framing: the problem this product solves for active women, then a brief overall impression (your thesis). ~90 words.]
## WSS™ Assessment
[For each criterion, an H3 heading EXACTLY in this form: "### Inclusive Fit & Proportional Sizing — X/5 ★★★★☆" (replace X with the score and show X filled ★ and (5−X) empty ☆ stars), then a short, experience-led paragraph (2–4 sentences) on how it performs, leading with strengths. Use the six criterion names IN THIS ORDER: Inclusive Fit & Proportional Sizing; Functional Performance in Use; Adequate Support Standards; Thermal Regulation & Material Performance; Genuine Female Design; Transparency & User Reviews.]
## Scores
Inclusive Fit & Proportional Sizing: X/5
Functional Performance in Use: X/5
Adequate Support Standards: X/5
Thermal Regulation & Material Performance: X/5
Genuine Female Design: X/5
Transparency & User Reviews: X/5
**Overall: X.X / 5 ★**
## Pros & Cons
[Two short, benefit-focused lists: what I loved, then a few gentle watch-outs (kept light).]
## Who It's For / Who It's Not For
## Size & Fit
## How It Compares
[A Markdown table comparing this product with 2-3 named competing women's products. Use proper Markdown table syntax with a header row and a separator row. Columns: Product | Price | Size Range | Key Strength | Our Verdict. Put THIS product in the first row. Keep each cell short (a few words).]
## The Verdict
[60–90 words. Warm and decisive — who should buy it and why.]
## FAQ
[Exactly 5 questions, each as an H3 (### Question?) with an answer under 50 words. Target Google featured snippets.]
END the review at the FAQ. Do NOT add a "Buy" section, a closing CTA, or any link — the page adds its own buy button. Start directly with ## Overview — no title, no H1, no "Reviewed by" byline. The Scores section is plain text lines (NEVER a table) and must NOT include any calculation, methodology or weighted-sum working.
VOICE & STYLE — follow closely:
- Write in the FIRST PERSON as the named reviewer ("I found", "I've used", "for me", "in my sessions"). Warm, enthusiastic and experience-led — a conversational review voice, never clinical testing language and never "the tester".
- Talk directly to the reader.
- Bold the product name, key features and important terms. Use the occasional italic for emphasis, the odd short sentence fragment for impact, colons to introduce lists or explanations, parentheses for clarifying details, and quotation marks around coined terms.
- Describe benefits in simple, evaluative terms (e.g. "true to size", "supportive", "stays put", "premium").
